<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="39" pageId="5" pageNumber="38" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[107,215,1392,1416]" box="[107,215,1392,1416]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[107,215,1392,1416]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[106,1096,1431,1639]" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">
Male antennal flagellomeres bear 2 whorls of hair-shaped translucent sensilla, one distal whorl of long sensilla and one basal whorl of shorter sensilla (
<figureCitation box="[677,757,1462,1486]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[194,225,1598,1620]" captionTargetBox="[217,1149,820,1592]" captionTargetId="figure-235@6.[193,1176,810,1596]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 1: Peromyia grovei sp. n., holotype male. – A: fourth antennal flagellomere, lateral view; - B: terminalia, ventral view; - C: tegmen, ventral view. Length of scale bar = 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4752389" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4752389/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
). Position of hair-shaped sensilla at the very bases of the flagellomere nodes is an unusual character state among peromyias, even though there are instances of sensilla that irregularly intermingle with the short subbasal setae that are universally present (see, for instance, 
<figureCitation box="[574,654,1554,1578]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="17.[110,141,1596,1618]" captionTargetBox="[114,1082,529,1575]" captionTargetId="figure-162@17.[110,1093,502,1594]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Fig. 8: Peromyia cinalatacinalata sp. n., holotype male. – A: fourth antennal flagellomere, lateral view; - B: terminalia, ventral view; - C: tegmen, ventral view. Length of scale bar = 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4752413" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4752413/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">Fig. 8A</figureCitation>
). Postocular bristles are usually arranged in 2 rows. Male terminalia have a diverse, often unusual structure, which is less pronounced in the representatives from 
<collectingRegion box="[321,422,1615,1639]" country="Australia" name="Tasmania" pageId="5" pageNumber="38">Tasmania</collectingRegion>
. This group gathers several species of previously uncertain affin-
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[189,1179,175,291]" pageId="6" pageNumber="39">
ity: 
<taxonomicName authority="JASCHHOF, 2004" authorityName="JASCHHOF" authorityYear="2004" box="[229,571,175,199]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Peromyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dissona">
<emphasis box="[229,396,175,199]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="39">Peromyia dissona</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="JASCHHOF, M. &amp; JASCHHOF, C." box="[403,571,176,199]" pageId="6" pageNumber="39" pagination="97 - 132" refId="ref10549" refString="JASCHHOF, M. &amp; JASCHHOF, C. 2004: Wood midges of New Zealand (Cecidomyiidae, Lestremiinae). Part III: Tribe Peromyiini and remarks on the composition, origin and relationships of the fauna as a whole. - Studia dipterologica 10 (2003) (1): 97 - 132." type="journal article" year="2004">JASCHHOF, 2004</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="JASCHHOF, 2004" authorityName="JASCHHOF" authorityYear="2004" box="[623,913,175,199]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Peromyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="praeclara">
<emphasis box="[623,735,175,199]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="39">P. praeclara</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="JASCHHOF, M. &amp; JASCHHOF, C." box="[741,913,176,199]" pageId="6" pageNumber="39" pagination="97 - 132" refId="ref10549" refString="JASCHHOF, M. &amp; JASCHHOF, C. 2004: Wood midges of New Zealand (Cecidomyiidae, Lestremiinae). Part III: Tribe Peromyiini and remarks on the composition, origin and relationships of the fauna as a whole. - Studia dipterologica 10 (2003) (1): 97 - 132." type="journal article" year="2004">JASCHHOF, 2004</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, both from 
<collectingCountry box="[1035,1175,176,197]" name="New Zealand" pageId="6" pageNumber="39">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
